		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><date>Jan. 18&#47;56</date></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>New York</placeName>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<placeName>144 Amos St.</placeName>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<placeName>Hudson St.</placeName></p>
				<p>Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Although I have &#40;only yesterday&#41; learned that you<lb/> cannot conveniently attend to any communication for your next number if<lb/> not sent in by the <date>10<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> yet since &#8220;where there&#39;s a will there is a way&#8221; I may<lb/> perhaps yet be in time.  Last month I have ventured to address you on the<lb/> subject of my Grammar&#44; but am now in doubt whether it has reached you&#44;<lb/> finding that I had misdirected it.  In it I stated my intention to &#40;as I am<lb/> persuaded to do&#41; send about circulars with the view of obtaining subsc<lb/>ribers to the work&#44; and was only waiting to be able to refer to some<lb/> testimonial from parties known to be competent judges.  I am<lb/> fully aware you not having seen the work cannot but deter you from<lb/> saying any thing about it&#44; but I think if you are inclined to favor one<lb/> you could do so by acquainting the public with the opinion of <persName>Drs Raphall</persName><lb/> &#38; <persName>Benisch</persName> on the merits of the said book.  The latter gentleman spontaneously<lb/> offered to do all he could to forward my object&#59; and accordingly you will find<lb/> in No. 99 of the Hebrew Observer Nos. 24. <date>1854</date> Pages 585. &#38; 590. how far he<lb/> has redeemed his pledge&#44; and that&#44; without any remuneration&#44; he has repeated<lb/> in the columns of his succeeding numbers more than a dozen times&#59; by means<lb/> of which the copyright together with the whole impression of the last edition<lb/> was greedily bought up&#44; so that I have not left a copy of it to present you with&#44;<lb/> or even one for my own use&#44; being now engaged here as a teacher.  You<lb/> will perceive from the enclosed what <persName>Dr R.</persName> said to the Editor of the<lb/> Asmonean respecting my Grammar&#59; but the latter declined the inser&#45;<lb/>tion of it&#44; not because he had the opportunity of giving his own opinion<lb/> on it&#44; for that&#44; of course&#44; anyhow&#44; was out of his power&#44; but because he would</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>do nothing for nothing&#59; which I am confident will not be the case<lb/> with you&#59; for you need not be reminded of <add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I remain&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">your&#39;s very respectfully</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">S. Newman</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Revd I Leeser</addressee></p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>The <addressee>Revd I. Leeser</addressee></p>
